This paper discusses the use of software defined network (SDN) at edge for traffic offloading in wireless networks, which falls under the category of computer networks (cs.NI). The paper also discusses the use of contract theory to incentivize third party access points (APs) to offload traffic, which falls under the category of information theory (cs.IT). Additionally, the paper discusses the issue of information asymmetry between the APs and the base stations (BSs), which could be considered a security issue and falls under the category of cryptography (cs.CR). The paper also discusses the use of pricing mechanisms to incentivize APs, which falls under the category of distributed, parallel, and cluster computing (cs.DC). Finally, the paper discusses the simulation results, which could be considered a form of computational complexity (cs.CY).
